  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements:\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Collecting and maintaining customer information\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR):\n- Identifying and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing reports with financial crime enforcement agencies\n- Monitoring unusual financial activity\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs:\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on money laundering prevention\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n4. Due diligence procedures:\n- Enhanced monitoring for high-risk customers\n- Investigating complex or unusual transaction patterns\n- Conducting background checks\n\n5. Regulatory compliance:\n- Following guidelines from agencies like FinCEN\n- Adhering to international standards\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n6. Transaction monitoring:\n- Using technological systems to track financial activities\n- Identifying potential money laundering patterns\n- Flagging suspicious transactions\n\nFailure to comply with these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.",
